authorMeta.name: castlesofscotland
text:
Welcoming in December from the Scottish Highlands ❄️

The first five locations featured in this video are from Inverness, Capital of the Scottish Highlands.

Inverness has played a key role throughout Scottish history. It was the capital of the Picts in the Middle Ages, during which time St. Columba visited in 565, converting the King of the Picts to Christianity. The kingdom of Alba would later be created when the kingdoms of the Scots and Picts were united in 843. This developed into the Scotland we know today.

Two hundred years later, Macbeth is said to have murdered King Duncan in his castle in Inverness. During this era, the town was the site of many battles and skirmishes. One of the most destructive occurred when the Abbot of Arbroath had his men burn down large parts of the town. The town was burnt down a second time in 1411 by Donald, Lord of the Isles.

During the Early Modern Age, there was substantial tension between the Highlands and the Scottish crown. This was shown in 1562 when the governor refused Mary, Queen of Scots entry - an act he would go on to be hanged for. In 1746 Inverness Castle was captured by Jacobites. When they were defeated at Culloden in April, the rebels were sacked from the castle. A large fortification was built to prevent such uprisings from occurring again.

The industry of Inverness was largely related to shipbuilding from the Middle Ages, however other industries grew such as whisky distilling. By the late 20th century, industry in Inverness had been transformed. Although it was still a busy port, tourism had become a major industry in the region, in large part due to the myth of the Loch Ness monster.

authorMeta.name: alex..glasgow
text:
One of the best hikes in the Southern Highlands (and still surprisingly underrated).

Connecting Ben Lui and Beinn a’ Chlèibhe makes for a particularly rewarding day hike, especially as you climb up into the corrie. There’s a moderately steep ascent, a river crossing and views that open out quickly.

The area is known for being exceptionally boggy, but if you catch it during a hard frost, it makes for much easier hiking. 

A few useful things to know if you’re planning it:
🏔️ Around 15km depending on your line
🥾 Some steep sections on Ben Lui
💩 This area can be EXTREMELY boggy
🌿 The walk in is fairly long and takes you through some forest, a river crossing is necessary (don’t say I never warned you) 💦
⏱️ A big day out, but a very rewarding one

If Ben Lui’s on your list, this is well worth doing as a pair.
Save this for later, and let me know if you’ve done it, or if it’s still on your list ⛰️

#scotland #hiking #benlui #beinnachleibh #highlands

authorMeta.name: stvnews
text:
People living in the north of Scotland are being invited to have their say on the potential reintroduction of lynx to the Highlands.

The species could return to the region as part of plans from a group of rewilding charities – with some 89,000 households to receive mail about the proposals in January.

A licence would be required from the government agency NatureScot before it could go ahead.

More than 40 meetings are planned to take place in the Highlands and Moray as part of a programme of public engagement starting on January 26.

The Lynx to Scotland partnership has been assessing how a potential reintroduction scheme could work since 2020.

authorMeta.name: lostinmovies2
text:
“Behind the scenes of Highlander, the Kurgan worked because Clancy Brown didn’t play him like a fantasy villain.

Clancy Brown treated him like a force of nature. 
Loud, cruel, unpredictable. 

No charm. 

No wink to the audience.

He leaned into physical intimidation. 

Big movements. 

Sudden stillness. 

Invading personal space even when the cameras weren’t rolling. 

The unease you feel on screen wasn’t accidental.

The accent, the leather, the laughter. 

None of it was toned down. 

The director encouraged him to go further, not rein it in.

 The Kurgan wasn’t meant to be cool. He was meant to feel dangerous.

Most villains explain themselves. 

The Kurgan doesn’t. 

He enjoys the damage and keeps moving.

That’s why he sticks.

He isn’t the hero’s opposite.

He’s the thing the hero refuses to become.” ⚔️🎬

text:
👇🏻 Your guide to these EPIC Winter Hikes!

1. Steall Falls, Scottish Highlands
A short but stunning hike to one of Scotland’s tallest waterfalls and a Harry Potter filming spot!

🥾: Moderate | ⏰ : 2 hrs | 🚘 : PH33 6SY

2. Chrome Hill, Peak District
Enjoy views over Parkhouse Hill also known as the Dragon’s Back for its unique shape, this hike is a photographer’s dream!

🥾: Moderate | ⏰ : 2.5 hrs | 🚘 : SK17 0BX

3. Llyn Idwal, North Wales
A magical 3-mile hike around a glacial lake surrounded by dramatic peaks.

🥾: Moderate | ⏰ : 3 hrs | 🚘 : LL57 3LZ

Don’t forget to pack warm layers, sturdy boots, snacks, water, and check the weather!

✨ Save this for your next winter adventure ✨

authorMeta.name: noms.brews.views
text:
Everyone visits the Scottish Highlands… but most people miss these stops 👀🏴󠁧󠁢󠁳󠁣󠁴󠁿⬇️

✨ Hidden Highlands — Part 1

🏰 Stirling Castle
Often skipped for Edinburgh, but one of the most important castles in Scotland — with panoramic views and far fewer crowds.

🌊 Kilchurn Castle
Dramatic ruins sitting right on the loch. No tour buses. Just quiet, cinematic Highlands scenery.

⚓ Oban
A laid-back coastal town with fresh seafood, ferry views, and a totally different Highlands vibe.

🏝 Castle Stalker
A postcard-perfect castle rising straight out of the water. Blink and you’ll miss it.

🚂 Glenfinnan Viaduct
Famous, yes — but still underrated when you catch it outside peak train times.

And that’s only half the list… 👀
Save this for later and stay tuned for Part 2 ✨

text:
❄️➡️💧➡️☀️
Nach dem Schnee kam das Tauwetter.
Nach dem Tauwetter die Überflutung.
Highland-Winter eben : wild, ungeschönt, echt.

Und dann… dieses eine Licht.
Die Sonne, die es endlich wieder über meinen Berg geschafft hat.
Zwei Monate lang unsichtbar und heute einfach da, als kleines Versprechen.

Manchmal sind es nicht die großen Dramen,
sondern ein paar Minuten Wintersonne,
die einen ganzen Tag retten.

Willkommen in Schottland. 🌄✨

Luxury hotel barges Spirit of Scotland and Scottish Highlander crossed paths at the iconic locks of Fort Augustus, right at the southern tip of stunning Loch Ness.

With autumn colours glowing across the hills and calm waters reflecting the Highlands at their best, it’s hard to imagine a more magical place for two incredible hotel barges to meet. 🍁⛰️

If you’ve ever dreamed of exploring Scotland at a slower, more soulful pace, this is it — hotel barge cruising at its finest.

Calling all Highland Cow lovers 📣 🐮

If you are like me and want to go to all and any highland cow experience you can find you need to add this to your list!

Minard Cows is a hands on two hour experience where you get to go into the paddock  meet all the cows under the guided supervision of their owners.

They will advise you of what cows you can hand feed, pat, cuddle and brush (let’s be real not all animals want human interaction haha) 

📍 Minard Cows - Southern Highlands 
💰$30PP
ℹ️ tours need to be booked in advanced via email 📧

Have any other suggestions drop them in the comments below because If there’s a highland cow you bet I’m there 👀

authorMeta.name: dreamlanderlife
text:
At dusk's gentle close, the Pygmy Flame Drakeling alights, its scales a vibrant tapestry of the day's last embers. Perched in quiet majesty, this tiny guardian surveys the world with eyes aglow with wisdom, its wings a miniature marvel, echoing the fiery sky. Here atop its secluded crag, it stands as a beacon of warmth and wonder, a jewel of the mountains, softly cradling the secrets of twilight.
